pull_request.title: Summary and social goals.
pull_request.body: This adds a general summary of the project and a list of social goals in order to keep the project positive.

pull_request.title: Add rule for building teams from projects, not people.
pull_request.body: This simple rule asks that managers build teams by drafting projects (such as `rails/rails`) instead of individual developers.

issue.title: Head to Head vs Points
issue.body:
Is this done baseball style where you track statistical categories?
is this football style where each player accrues points?

comment.body:
I need to familiarize myself with how fantasy leagues work, but isn't it often the case that in a manager-v-manager setup, one manager would compete against another, and the winner for the week would add that win to their record? Then we start the points over again from scratch with another manager-v-manager and another week.

Or is that not how it works?

issue.title: Positions
issue.body:
Do we want to have positions? What are the positions?

The best idea I have is that positions are programming languages. If you draft a player for JavaScript, than only commits that include JavaScript changes are included in their commit stats.

comment.body:
Could it be that, for a specific week, a manager selects players and assigns them to positions (Committer, Pull Request Originator, Pull Request Merger) and accrues points based on what the player does that week?

A manager could then shift a player to a different position for a subsequent week.

issue.title: Player pool and draft
issue.body: How do we define a player pool? How do people efficiently draft?

comment.body:
It could be easy for the league to degrade into yet-another-stress on the backs of open source committers.

In order to keep that from happening, I think that developers should have to opt-in to being included in a league.

Also, I think we should consider a scenario where only projects are drafted, not people. Then it would reduce the pressure on individuals.
